Continuous economic development and evolving social systems have created unique 
challenges for school health personnel in Taiwan. Due in part to economic growth 
and an improving health care system, average life expectancy has increased 
markedly for males and females since 1950. Traditional leading causes of death 
such as pneumonia, tuberculosis, and gastroenteritis have been replaced by 
accidents, neoplasms, and cardiovascular diseases. Schoolchildren suffer from 
various disorders that include hepatitis B, dental caries, and health problems 
related to scholastic pressure such as myopia, anxiety, and depression. However, 
