848. Biosystems. 1990;24(2):119-25. doi: 10.1016/0303-2647(90)90004-k.

A predictive model for life expectancy curves.

Kloeden PE(1), Rössler OE, Rössler R.

Author information:
(1)School of Mathematics and Physical Sciences, Murdoch University, Western 
Australia.

Life expectancy curves have a characteristic ominous shape that has fascinated 
scientists for centuries. Medawar was the first to explain this shape, 
specifically the steeply rising proneness of an average individual to die as a 
function of age, in evolutionary terms. The idea was that the "selective value" 
of the individual decreases as it has triggered other individuals taking its 
place (and carrying its genes) into existence. We demonstrate that this idea can 
be turned into a quantitative model. The resulting 4-parameter function 
reproduces well two well-known life expectancy curves from the first half of 
this century. Moreover, the easily interpretable parameters (3 of the 4) seem 
intuitively reasonable.

DOI: 10.1016/0303-2647(90)90004-k
