866. Int J Radiat Oncol Biol Phys. 1990 Nov;19(5):1303-8. doi: 
10.1016/0360-3016(90)90249-j.

Cancer occurring after radiotherapy and chemotherapy.

Holm LE(1).

Author information:
(1)Department of Cancer Prevention, Radiumhemmet, Karolinska Hospital, 
Stockholm, Sweden.

Radiotherapy and chemotherapy can effectively control cancer but can also cause 
new cancers to develop as long-term complications. Almost all types of cancer 
have been associated with radiotherapy. The breast, thyroid, and bone marrow are 
the organs most susceptible to radiation carcinogenesis. The bone marrow is also 
most frequently involved by chemotherapy and the leukemia risk is much higher 
than after radiotherapy. The combination of intensive radiotherapy and 
chemotherapy is particularly leukemogenic. The latent period between 
radiotherapy/chemotherapy and the appearance of a second primary cancer ranges 
from a few years to several decades. The risk for a second primary cancer 
following radiotherapy or chemotherapy emphasizes the need for life long 
follow-up of patients receiving such treatments. This is particularly the case 
in individuals with long life expectancy, for example, patients treated for 
childhood neoplasms. The benefits of radiotherapy and chemotherapy in oncology 
exceed the risks for second primary cancers. Efforts should be directed towards 
